E. COLI O104 - EUROPEAN UNION (27): UPDATE, FENUGREEK SEED SUSPECTED
********************************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this update:
[1] ECDC update with French cases without German link
[2] Epidemiological fenugreek seed link

******
[1] ECDC update with French cases without German link
Date: Wed 29 Jun 2011
Source: European Center for Disease Control (ECDC) [edited]
http://ecdc.europa.eu/en/activities/sciadvice/Lists/ECDC%20Reviews/ECDC_DispForm.aspx?List=512ff74f-77d4-4ad8-b6d6-bf0f23083f30&ID=1124&RootFolder=%2Fen%2Factivities%2Fsciadvice%2FLists%2FECDC%20Reviews


Update since 28 Jun 2011
------------------------
In the EU/EEA, 885 HUS [hemolytic uremic syndrome] cases, including
31 deaths, and 3170 non-HUS cases, including 17 deaths have so far
been reported. Germany reports 28 non-HUS STEC [Shiga toxin producing
_Escherichia coli_] cases since the last update. Sweden reports 1 new
non-HUS STEC case, who does not have any known links to Germany, and
claims not to have eaten sprouts. The latest known date of onset of
diarrhea for cases is 23 Jun 2011 in Germany.

On Fri 24 Jun 2011, France reported a cluster of patients with bloody
diarrhea, who had participated in an event in the commune of Begles
around Bordeaux on 8 Jun 2011. As of 28 Jun 2011, 8 cases of bloody
diarrhea and a further 8 cases with HUS have been identified. 11 of
these patients had attended the event in Begles. They are 7 women and
4 men, between 31 and 64 years of age. Infection with _E. coli_
O104:H4 has been confirmed for 4 patients with HUS.

The French authorities are investigating this new cluster of STEC. 9
of the cases reported having eaten sprouts at the event on 8 Jun 2011,
and leftovers are currently being analyzed. These suspected sprouts
were locally produced, and were not imported from the farm implicated
in the outbreak in Germany.

Thorough investigations are now being carried out to determine the
suspected vehicle of infection for the cases reported in the French
cluster, and whether there is any link between that cluster and the
large outbreak reported from Germany.

--
