<promed@promedmail.org>

[A common link at the seed level would explain why locally sprouted
produce could contain the same pathogen. We await the probable finding
of other cases like the Swedish non-linked case and another previously
reported from Denmark, and the epidemiology of those cases.

Fenugreek (_Trigonella foenum-graecum_) is a plant in the family
Fabaceae. Fenugreek is used both as a herb (the leaves) and as a spice
(the seed, often called methi). The plant is cultivated worldwide as a
semi-arid crop and is a common ingredient in many curries -- see more
info and picture in http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fenugreek. -
Mod.LL]


[I fail to see how the finger can be pointed at Egypt when the report
says:
"But the agencies cautioned that there is no lab evidence yet tying
the seeds to the outbreaks." - Mod.JW]
